CF HB 1118
By: Senators Gile, Beidle, Hester, Hettleman, and King
Introduced and read first time: February 6, 2026
Assigned to: Finance
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Senate action: Adopted
Read second time: March 19, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Health, Health Insurance, and Health Occupations – Perinatal Mental
3 Behavioral Health Conditions
4 FOR the purpose of requiring carriers to provide a standing referral to a mental behavioral
5 health care provider for a certain period of time; clarifying the application of
6 provisions requiring carriers to allow a member to obtain a referral to a provider who
7 is not part of the carrier’s provider network when seeking care for a mental health
8 condition in certain circumstances; requiring the Maryland Medical Assistance
9 Program and certain insurers, nonprofit health service plans, and health
10 maintenance organizations to provide coverage for screening for perinatal mental
11 behavioral health conditions at certain times; altering and establishing
12 requirements related to the identification and development of training programs
13 that improve early identification of perinatal mental behavioral health conditions;
14 requiring the Maryland Department of Health to establish a perinatal mental health
15 condition screening program certain health care providers to screen for perinatal
16 behavioral health conditions; requiring the Maryland Department of Health to
17 identify certain screening tools and to assist certain health care providers with
18 accessing resources and referral services related to screening for perinatal
19 behavioral health conditions; requiring certain applicants for the renewal of a health
20 occupation license or certificate to provide documentation that the applicant
21 completed continuing education credit hours health occupations boards to grant a
22 certain number of hours of continuing education credits for each hour of continuing
23 education completed by certain individuals on perinatal mental behavioral health
24 conditions; and generally relating to perinatal mental behavioral health conditions.
