6 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
7 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
8 Article – Health – General
9 15–103.
10 (a) (1) The Secretary shall administer the Maryland Medical Assistance
11 Program.
12 (2) The Program:
13 (xxvii) Beginning on January 1, 2026, if providing coverage for the
14 delivery of anesthesia, shall provide coverage for the delivery of anesthesia in accordance
15 with § 15–862 of the Insurance Article; [and]
16 (xxviii) Beginning on January 1, 2026, shall provide calcium score
17 testing in accordance with § 15–863 of the Insurance Article; AND
18 (XXIX) BEGINNING ON JANUARY 1, 2027, SHALL PROVIDE
19 COVERAGE FOR SCREENING FOR PERINATAL BEHAVIORAL HEALTH CONDITIONS AT
20 WELL VISITS WITHIN THE FIRST YEAR OF THE CHILD’S LIFE, AS DETERMINED
21 APPROPRIATE BY THE TREATING HEALTH CARE PROVIDER.
22 Article – Insurance
23 15–830.
24 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
25 (2) “Carrier” means:
26 (i) an insurer that offers health insurance other than long–term
27 care insurance or disability insurance;
28 (ii) a nonprofit health service plan;
29 (iii) a health maintenance organization;

4 SENATE BILL 891
1 (iv) a dental plan organization; or
2 (v) except for a managed care organization as defined in Title 15,
3 Subtitle 1 of the Health – General Article, any other person that provides health benefit
4 plans subject to State regulation.
5 (3) (i) “Member” means an individual entitled to health care benefits
6 under a policy or plan issued or delivered in the State by a carrier.
7 (ii) “Member” includes a subscriber.
8 (4) “MENTAL HEALTH DISORDER” INCLUDES A PERINATAL MENTAL
9 HEALTH CONDITION.
10 [(4)] (5) “Nonphysician specialist” means a health care provider:
11 (i) 1. who is not a physician;
12 2. who is licensed or certified under the Health Occupations
13 Article; and
14 3. who is certified or trained to treat or provide health care
15 services for a specified condition or disease in a manner that is within the scope of the
16 license or certification of the health care provider; or
17 (ii) that is licensed as a behavioral health program under § 7.5–401
18 of the Health – General Article.
19 (6) (5) (I) “PERINATAL MENTAL BEHAVIORAL HEALTH
20 CONDITION” MEANS A MENTAL BEHAVIORAL HEALTH CONDITION OCCURRING
21 DURING PREGNANCY, THE POSTPARTUM PERIOD, OR THE PERINATAL PERIOD OR
22 WITHIN 1 YEAR AFTER THE CONCLUSION OF A PREGNANCY, INCLUDING A
23 PREGNANCY THAT DOES NOT RESULT IN A LIVE BIRTH.
24 (II) “PERINATAL MENTAL BEHAVIORAL HEALTH CONDITION”
25 INCLUDES POSTPARTUM DEPRESSION.
26 [(5)] (7) (6) (i) “Provider panel” means the providers that contract with a
27 carrier either directly or through a subcontracting entity to provide health care services to
28 enrollees of the carrier.
29 (ii) “Provider panel” does not include an arrangement in which any
30 provider may participate solely by contracting with the carrier to provide health care
31 services at a discounted fee–for–service rate.

SENATE BILL 891 5
1 [(6)] (8) (7) “Specialist” means a physician who is certified or trained to
2 practice in a specified field of medicine and who is not designated as a primary care provider
3 by the carrier.
4 (c) (1) (I) Notwithstanding any other provision of this section, a member
5 who is pregnant shall receive a standing referral to an obstetrician, in accordance with this
6 subsection.
7 [(2)] (II) After the member who is pregnant receives a standing referral to
8 an obstetrician, the obstetrician is responsible for the primary management of the
9 member’s pregnancy, including the issuance of referrals in accordance with the carrier’s
10 policies and procedures, through the postpartum period.
11 (2) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER PROVISION OF THIS SECTION, A
12 MEMBER SHALL RECEIVE A STANDING REFERRAL TO A MENTAL HEALTH CARE
13 PROVIDER, IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SUBSECTION, FOR THE DURATION OF THE
14 MEMBER’S PREGNANCY AND 1 YEAR AFTER THE MEMBER GIVES BIRTH TO A
15 BEHAVIORAL HEALTH CARE PROVIDER ACTING WITHIN THE SCOPE OF THE
16 PROVIDER’S LICENSE, INCLUDING A PSYCHIATRIST, PSYCHOLOGIST, LICENSED
17 SOCIAL WORKER–CLINICAL, OR LICENSED PROFESSIONAL COUNSELOR FOR:
18 (I) THE BEHAVIORAL HEALTH SERVICES RECOGNIZED BY THE
19 UNITED STATES PREVENTIVE SERVICES TASK FORCE AS PREVENTIVE BENEFITS;
20 AND
21 (II) THE DURATION OF THE MEMBER’S PREGNANCY AND 1 YEAR
22 AFTER THE CONCLUSION OF THE PREGNANCY.
23 (3) A written treatment plan may not be required when a standing referral
24 is to an obstetrician OR MENTAL BEHAVIORAL HEALTH CARE PROVIDER under this
25 subsection.
26 (d) (1) Each carrier shall establish and implement a procedure by which a
27 member may request a referral to a specialist or nonphysician specialist who is not part of
28 the carrier’s provider panel in accordance with this subsection.
29 (2) The procedure shall provide for a referral to a specialist or nonphysician
30 specialist who is not part of the carrier’s provider panel if:
31 (i) 1. the member is diagnosed with a condition or disease that
32 requires specialized health care services or medical care; and
33 2. A. the carrier does not have in its provider panel a
34 specialist or nonphysician specialist with the professional training and expertise to treat or
35 provide health care services for the condition or disease; or

6 SENATE BILL 891
1 B. the carrier cannot provide reasonable access to a specialist
2 or nonphysician specialist with the professional training and expertise to treat or provide
3 health care services for the condition or disease without unreasonable delay or travel,
4 including within the reasonable appointment waiting time and travel distance standards
5 established in regulation for mental health and substance use disorder services; or
6 (ii) 1. the member is seeking mental health or substance use
7 disorder care; and
8 2. the carrier cannot provide reasonable access to a specialist
9 or nonphysician specialist within the reasonable appointment waiting time and travel
10 distance standards established in regulation for mental health and substance use disorder
11 services.
12 (3) The procedure shall ensure that a request to obtain a referral to a
13 specialist or nonphysician specialist who is not part of the carrier’s provider panel is
14 addressed in a timely manner that is:
15 (i) appropriate for the member’s condition; and
16 (ii) in accordance with the timeliness requirements for
17 determinations made by private review agents under § 15–10B–06 of this title.
18 (4) If a member cannot access mental health or substance use disorder
19 services through the referral requirements under paragraphs (2) and (3) of this subsection,
20 the procedure shall require the carrier to provide additional assistance to the member in
21 identifying and arranging coverage of mental health or substance use disorder services by
22 a specialist or nonphysician specialist who is not part of the carrier’s provider panel.
23 (5) If a carrier approves a member’s request for a referral made in
24 accordance with this subsection, the carrier may not require utilization review other than
25 what would be required if the covered benefit were provided by a provider on the carrier’s
26 provider panel.
27 (6) The procedure may not be used by a carrier as a substitute for
28 establishing and maintaining a sufficient provider network in accordance with § 15–112 of
29 this title.
30 (7) Each carrier shall:
31 (i) have a system in place that documents all requests to obtain a
32 referral to receive a covered service from a specialist or nonphysician specialist who is not
33 part of the carrier’s provider panel;
34 (ii) inform members of the procedure to request a referral under
35 paragraph (1) of this subsection; and

